JHU RM Final Project: Analysis of Transmission Type and MPG using mtcars Dataset

Jasmine Georgina

2025-03-02

Executive Summary

This report examines whether automatic or manual transmission is better for miles per gallon (MPG) using the mtcars dataset. Through exploratory data analysis and regression modeling, we find that manual transmissions tend to offer better fuel efficiency compared to automatic transmissions. A simple linear regression model suggests that manual transmission vehicles achieve 7.24 more MPG on average than automatic vehicles. However, after controlling for confounding factors such as weight and horsepower, the adjusted difference is reduced to 2.94 MPG. These findings indicate that while manual transmissions have a fuel efficiency advantage, other factors significantly contribute to the observed differences.

Data Description

The mtcars dataset in R is a built-in collection of data about 32 different car models, containing information on various attributes like miles per gallon (mpg), number of cylinders (cyl), horsepower (hp), weight, and other performance metrics, originally extracted from the 1974 Motor Trend US magazine, making it a popular dataset for practicing data analysis and visualization in statistics and data science.

Key points about the mtcars dataset:

  1. Source: Data from the 1974 Motor Trend US magazine.

  2. Number of observations: 32 cars

  3. Number of variables: 11

Some important variables in the mtcars dataset:

  • mpg: Miles per gallon

  • cyl: Number of cylinders in the engine

  • hp: Horsepower

  • wt: Weight of the car

  • am: Transmission type (0 = automatic, 1 = manual)

  • gear: Number of gears carb: Number of carburetors

A boxplot of MPG by transmission type:

ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = am, y = mpg, fill = am)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "MPG by Transmission Type", x = "Transmission", y = "MPG")

The plot suggests manual transmissions tend to have higher MPG than automatic ones.

Regression Analysis

We fit two models: a simple linear model using only transmission type and a multiple linear regression controlling for additional variables.

pairs(mpg ~ ., data= mtcars)

Model 1: Simple Linear Regression

model1 <- lm(mpg ~ am, data = mtcars)

Model Diagnosis

Residual plots confirm that assumptions of linear regression are largely met:

par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(model2)

The residuals appear to be randomly distributed, indicating a well-fitted model.

Conclusion

In general, manual transmissions provide better fuel efficiency than automatic transmissions. The estimated MPG difference is 7.24 when considering only transmission type, but it reduces to 2.94 after adjusting for weight and horsepower. This suggests that while transmission type influences MPG, other vehicle characteristics also play a significant role. These results support the claim that manual transmissions tend to be more fuel-efficient but highlight the need to consider multiple factors when evaluating vehicle performance.
